{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-jsx","path":"/css-responsive-fonts","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1 id=\"css-responsive-fonts\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#css-responsive-fonts\" aria-label=\"css responsive fonts permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>CSS Responsive Fonts</h1>\n<p>Making sure your fonts adapt to different screen layouts is very important. To help us with this, we often use <strong>rem</strong> units, which are fluid. <strong>REM</strong> stands for <em>root em</em>. <strong>1rem</strong> = the root font size, i.e. the default font size of the browser, or the one the user sets. On most browsers, the default font size is <strong>16px</strong>, so <strong>1rem</strong> would equal <strong>16px</strong>.</p>\n<p>You can manually set the root font size like this:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"css\"><pre class=\"language-css\"><code class=\"language-css\"><span class=\"token selector\">html</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   <span class=\"token property\">font-size</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> 10px<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span> <span class=\"token comment\">/* You can put your desired default font size */</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Therefore, <strong>rem</strong> all font sizes will refer to the 10px. So </p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"css\"><pre class=\"language-css\"><code class=\"language-css\"><span class=\"token selector\">p</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   <span class=\"token property\">font-size</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> 1rem<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span> <span class=\"token comment\">/* 1rem = 1 x 10px = 10px*/</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"token selector\">h1</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n   <span class=\"token property\">font-size</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> 2rem<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span> <span class=\"token comment\">/* 2rem = 2 x 10px = 20px */</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Doing this makes the fonts respond to whatever font size is the default or is set by the use. It is much better the using non-fluid units like PXs. You can read more about CSS units on the <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/CSS/Building_blocks/Values_and_units\">Mozilla Documentaion Page</a></p>","timeToRead":1,"excerpt":"CSS Responsive Fonts Making sure your fonts adapt to different screen layouts is very important. To help us with this, we often use rem…","frontmatter":{"title":"CSS Responsive Fonts","date":"2020-10-26 13:59:31 +0100","categories":["other"],"tags":["CSS","Responsive Fonts","CSS Fonts"],"description":null,"keywords":"CSS, Responsive Fonts, CSS Fonts","author":"Rabson J Phiri","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":204,"height":132,"src":"/static/196a2651664d4af8da2ae6b5dce6a2a2/02521/other.png","srcSet":"/static/196a2651664d4af8da2ae6b5dce6a2a2/02521/other.png 1x"}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/css-responsive-fonts","date":"2020-10-26T12:59:31.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/css-responsive-fonts","nexttitle":"Changes behavior interface - Java 8","nextslug":"/changes-behavior-interface-java-8","prevtitle":"JavaScript sort trick","prevslug":"/javascript-sort-trick","tagList":["abstraction","